<paragraph id="766F36CCFFD0FFFEBCCBF8851320FE50" blockId="1.[136,1452,1880,2077]" lastBlockId="2.[136,1453,236,1544]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="268" pageId="1" pageNumber="267">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD0FFFDBD43F8851478F835" authority="Jiang &amp; Li" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Li" box="[309,599,1914,1938]" class="Arachnida" family="Pilosarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="267" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pilosarachnidae Jiang &amp; Li</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD0FFFDBE17F88514E6F835" bold="true" box="[609,713,1914,1938]" pageId="1" pageNumber="267">fam. nov.</emphasis>
can be distinguished from Synspermiata by the presence of AME and the morphology of bulb which is not piriform; from Araneoidea and Palpimanoidea by the presence of cribellum; from Dionycha of RTA clade by the presence of 
<collectionCode id="10C1AE09FFD0FFFDBE19F83F14B2F87F" box="[623,669,1984,2008]" country="0" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/hz43-zma8" name="International Transit Centre" pageId="1" pageNumber="267">ITC</collectionCode>
. The new family resembles modern cribellate RTA clade spiders (
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD0FFFDB908F83F138AF870" box="[1406,1445,1984,2007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="267">e.g.</emphasis>
, members of marronoid clade such as 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD0FFFDBE6EF81D15E3F85D" authority="O. Pickard-Cambridge, 1871" authorityName="O. Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1871" box="[536,972,2018,2042]" class="Arachnida" family="Dictynidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="267" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Dictynidae O. Pickard-Cambridge, 1871</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD0FFFDBFA1F81D12E7F85D" authority="Pocock, 1895" authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1895" box="[983,1224,2018,2042]" class="Arachnida" family="Desidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="267" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Desidae Pocock, 1895</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD0FFFDB8A5F81C12DDF85D" box="[1235,1266,2019,2042]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="267">etc</emphasis>
.) by the shape of cymbium, attaching angle of bulb relative to cymbium and the arrangement of tegular apophyses (
<figureCitation id="EEEB2A49FFD0FFFDB8DBF7FA1307F7BA" box="[1197,1320,2053,2077]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[155,218,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-71@5.[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pilosarachne ju Jiang &amp; Li, gen. &amp; sp. nov., holotype male. A. Left palp, retrolateral view. B. Bulb of left palp, ventral view. C. Right palp, dorsal view, horizontally flipped for the sake of comparison. D. Left palp, ventral view. Scale bars: A, Câ€“D=0.5 mm; B=0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5367239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5367239/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="267">Figs 3Aâ€“D</figureCitation>
), but can be easily distinguished by the absence of an RTA and the presence of serrate accessory claw setae. 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEB8F2FF131388FEA3" authority="Jiang &amp; Li" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Li" box="[1156,1447,236,261]" class="Arachnida" family="Pilosarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pilosarachnidae Jiang &amp; Li</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBCFEFEF016DCFE80" bold="true" box="[136,243,271,295]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">fam. nov.</emphasis>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBD19FEF01450FE80" authority="Thorell, 1870" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1870" box="[367,639,271,295]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hersiliidae Thorell, 1870</taxonomicName>
by the presence of feathery scales (in the sense of 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEB8C2FEF013B0FE80" author="Griswold &amp; Ramirez &amp; Coddington &amp; Platnick &amp; Atlas of phylogenetic data for entelegyne spiders &amp; Araneae &amp; Araneomorphae &amp; Entelegynae &amp; Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences" box="[1204,1439,271,295]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" pagination="1 - 324" refId="ref8013" refString="Griswold, C. E., Ramirez, M. J., Coddington, J. A., Platnick, N. I. 2005. Atlas of phylogenetic data for entelegyne spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae: Entelegynae) with comments on their phylogeny. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 56 (Suppl. II): 1 - 324." type="journal article" year="2005">
Griswold 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEB956FEEF1377FE80" box="[1312,1368,271,295]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
), discoid tegulum, presence of median apophysis and filiform embolus, but can be distinguished from the latter by the short clypeus, eye domain in an anterior-most position rather than in the center of the carapace, posterior lateral spinnerets not elongated and the presence of cribellum. The family also resembles 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBF13FE88128DFE28" authority="C. L. Koch, 1850" authorityName="C. L. Koch" authorityYear="1850" box="[869,1186,375,399]" class="Arachnida" family="Deinopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Deinopidae C. L. Koch, 1850</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEB8AEFE881691FE15" authority="Thorell, 1869" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1869" class="Arachnida" family="Uloboridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Uloboridae Thorell, 1869</taxonomicName>
by the presence of abundant feathery scales, a cribellum, and serrate accessory claw setae, but can be distinguished from both families by the absence of tarsal spines and contiguous lateral eyes; and additionally, from 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEB892FE431370FE73" authorityName="C. L. Koch" authorityYear="1850" box="[1252,1375,444,468]" class="Arachnida" family="Deinopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Deinopidae</taxonomicName>
by the absence of enlarged PME and coiled embolus; and from 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBE93FE201572FE50" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1869" box="[741,861,479,503]" class="Arachnida" family="Uloboridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Uloboridae</taxonomicName>
by the absence of femoral trichobothria.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="766F36CCFFD3FFFEBCCBFDFD152EFBC0" blockId="2.[136,1453,236,1544]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">
As for the extinct cribellate families at the same time and locality (
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBF0DFDFD15B4FDBE" box="[891,923,514,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">i.e.</emphasis>
, 
<collectingRegion id="B414F82EFFD3FFFEBFDEFDFD15DAFDBD" box="[936,1013,514,538]" country="Myanmar" name="Kachin" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Kachin</collectingRegion>
amber), 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEB825FDFD1340FDBD" authority="Jiang &amp; Li" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Li" box="[1107,1391,514,538]" class="Arachnida" family="Pilosarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pilosarachnidae Jiang &amp;Li</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEB90EFDFE1698FD9B" bold="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">fam. nov.</emphasis>
can generally be distinguished from most cribellate families by the presence of rich feathery scales on carapace, abdomen and all appendages, such as â€  
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBE1CFDB815DBFDF8" authority="Wunderlich, 2018" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2018" box="[618,1012,583,607]" class="Arachnida" family="Alteruloboridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Alteruloboridae 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBF51FDB815DBFDF8" author="Wunderlich" box="[807,1012,583,607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9407" refString="Wunderlich, J., Muller, P. 2018. Fossil spiders (Araneae) in Cretaceous Burmese amber. In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 11. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 1 - 167." type="book" year="2018">Wunderlich, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, â€  
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEB862FDB81388FDF8" authority="Wunderlich, 2018" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2018" box="[1044,1447,583,607]" class="Arachnida" family="Frateruloboridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Frateruloboridae 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEB8ACFDB81388FDF8" author="Wunderlich" box="[1242,1447,583,607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9407" refString="Wunderlich, J., Muller, P. 2018. Fossil spiders (Araneae) in Cretaceous Burmese amber. In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 11. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 1 - 167." type="book" year="2018">Wunderlich, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, â€  
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBCE5FD9517D6FD25" authority="Wunderlich, 2017" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2017" box="[147,505,618,642]" class="Arachnida" family="Praearaneidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Praearaneidae 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBD43FD9517D6FD25" author="Wunderlich" box="[309,505,618,642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9324" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2017. New and rare fossil spiders (Araneae) in mid Cretaceous amber from Myanmar (Burma), including the description of new extinct families of the suborders Mesothelae and Opisthothelae as well as notes on the taxonomy, the evolution and the biogeography of the Mesothelae. In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 10. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 72 - 279." type="book" year="2017">Wunderlich, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and â€  
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBE48FD9515E0FD25" authority="Wunderlich, 2018" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2018" box="[574,975,618,642]" class="Arachnida" family="Protoaraneoididae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Protoaraneoididae 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBF7AFD9515E0FD25" author="Wunderlich" box="[780,975,618,642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9407" refString="Wunderlich, J., Muller, P. 2018. Fossil spiders (Araneae) in Cretaceous Burmese amber. In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 11. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 1 - 167." type="book" year="2018">Wunderlich, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
