amber; 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBD89FD5014E6FD60" author="Selden" box="[511,713,687,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" pagination="775 - 778" refId="ref8566" refString="Selden, P. A., Shih, C. - K., Ren, D. 2011. A golden orb-weaver spider (Araneae: Nephilidae: Nephila) from the Middle Jurassic of China. Biology Letters, 7: 775 - 778. doi: 10.1098 / rsbl. 2011.0228." type="journal article" year="2011">
Selden 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBE39FD4F14AAFD60" box="[591,645,687,711]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">et al.</emphasis>
, 2011
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBEA2FD501522FD60" author="Selden" box="[724,781,687,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" pagination="1171 - 1181" refId="ref8622" refString="Selden, P. A., Shih, C. - K., Ren, D. 2013. A giant spider from the Jurassic of China reveals greater diversity of the orbicularian stem group. Naturwissenschaften, 100: 1171 - 1181. doi: 10.1007 / s 00114 - 013 - 1121 - 7." type="journal article" year="2013">2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBF6EFD5015F5FD60" author="Wunderlich" box="[792,986,687,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9255" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2015. On the evolution and the classification of spiders, the Mesozoic spider faunas, and descriptions of new Cretaceous taxa mainly in amber from Myanmar (Burma) (Arachnida: Araneae). In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 9. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 21 - 408." type="book" year="2015">Wunderlich, 2015</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBF93FD501233FD60" author="Wunderlich" box="[997,1052,687,711]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9324" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2017. New and rare fossil spiders (Araneae) in mid Cretaceous amber from Myanmar (Burma), including the description of new extinct families of the suborders Mesothelae and Opisthothelae as well as notes on the taxonomy, the evolution and the biogeography of the Mesothelae. In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 10. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 72 - 279." type="book" year="2017">2017</bibRefCitation>
) by the presence of serrate accessory claw setae, and with the presence of femoral spines and apical spines on male palpal tibia, but can be distinguished by the following combination of characters: 1. the absence of extremely long femur of male palp (palpal femur of almost identical length to femur III and shorter than carapace length), while male palpal femur in two subfamilies of 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEB895FCE81384FC88" box="[1251,1451,791,815]" class="Arachnida" family="Mongolarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mongolarachnidae</taxonomicName>
(Longissipalpinae and Pedipalparaneinae) is longer than femur III and the length of carapace; 2. the contiguous lateral eyes; 3. the spoon-like membranous conductor (
<figureCitation id="EEEB2A49FFD3FFFEBE3FFCA314CEFCD3" box="[585,737,860,884]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[155,218,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-71@5.[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pilosarachne ju Jiang &amp; Li, gen. &amp; sp. nov., holotype male. A. Left palp, retrolateral view. B. Bulb of left palp, ventral view. C. Right palp, dorsal view, horizontally flipped for the sake of comparison. D. Left palp, ventral view. Scale bars: A, Câ€“D=0.5 mm; B=0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5367239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5367239/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Figs 3Aâ€“B, D</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBF26FCA31237FCD3" box="[848,1048,860,884]" class="Arachnida" family="Mongolarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mongolarachnidae</taxonomicName>
the conductor is absent (see 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEB93FFCA3171DFC30" author="Selden" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" pagination="1171 - 1181" refId="ref8622" refString="Selden, P. A., Shih, C. - K., Ren, D. 2013. A giant spider from the Jurassic of China reveals greater diversity of the orbicularian stem group. Naturwissenschaften, 100: 1171 - 1181. doi: 10.1007 / s 00114 - 013 - 1121 - 7." type="journal article" year="2013">
Selden 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEB9EEFCA2168BFC30" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">et al.</emphasis>
, 2013: 1175
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 2f) or a filiform tegular apophysis (
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBE8AFC7F150CFC30" box="[764,803,896,919]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">e.g.</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBF45FC801248FC30" author="Wunderlich" box="[819,1127,895,919]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9255" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2015. On the evolution and the classification of spiders, the Mesozoic spider faunas, and descriptions of new Cretaceous taxa mainly in amber from Myanmar (Burma) (Arachnida: Araneae). In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 9. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 21 - 408." type="book" year="2015">Wunderlich, 2015: 383â€“384</bibRefCitation>
, figs 186â€“190) or a fork-like sclerotized apophysis (see 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBDD7FC5D14B9FC1D" author="Wunderlich" box="[417,662,929,954]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9255" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2015. On the evolution and the classification of spiders, the Mesozoic spider faunas, and descriptions of new Cretaceous taxa mainly in amber from Myanmar (Burma) (Arachnida: Araneae). In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 9. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 21 - 408." type="book" year="2015">Wunderlich, 2015: 384</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 197) is present instead. 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBFC8FC5D12A8FC1D" author="Wunderlich" box="[958,1159,929,954]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9255" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2015. On the evolution and the classification of spiders, the Mesozoic spider faunas, and descriptions of new Cretaceous taxa mainly in amber from Myanmar (Burma) (Arachnida: Araneae). In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 9. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 21 - 408." type="book" year="2015">Wunderlich (2015)</bibRefCitation>
provided a set of characters for 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBCC4FC3B1755FC7B" box="[178,378,964,988]" class="Arachnida" family="Mongolarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mongolarachnidae</taxonomicName>
with description of two new genera from this family, 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBFADFC3A15D4FC7B" box="[987,1019,965,988]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">i.e.</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEB87BFC3B1355FC7B" authority="Wunderlich, 2015" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2015" box="[1037,1402,964,988]" class="Arachnida" genus="Longissipalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEB87BFC3B1280FC7B" box="[1037,1199,964,988]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Longissipalpus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEB8CEFC3B1355FC7B" author="Wunderlich" box="[1208,1402,964,988]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9255" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2015. On the evolution and the classification of spiders, the Mesozoic spider faunas, and descriptions of new Cretaceous taxa mainly in amber from Myanmar (Burma) (Arachnida: Araneae). In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 9. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 21 - 408." type="book" year="2015">Wunderlich, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBCFEFC181428FC58" authority="Wunderlich, 2015" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2015" box="[136,519,999,1023]" class="Arachnida" genus="Pedipalparaneus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBCFEFC181711FC58" box="[136,318,999,1023]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Pedipalparaneus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBD33FC181428FC58" author="Wunderlich" box="[325,519,999,1023]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" refId="ref9255" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2015. On the evolution and the classification of spiders, the Mesozoic spider faunas, and descriptions of new Cretaceous taxa mainly in amber from Myanmar (Burma) (Arachnida: Araneae). In: Wunderlich, J. (ed.), Beitrage zur Araneologie, Vol. 9. Hirschberg, Germany. pp. 21 - 408." type="book" year="2015">Wunderlich, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, in which he concluded that feathery hairs (equivalent to feathery scales in 
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEB958FC1816C7FB86" author="Griswold &amp; Ramirez &amp; Coddington &amp; Platnick &amp; Atlas of phylogenetic data for entelegyne spiders &amp; Araneae &amp; Araneomorphae &amp; Entelegynae &amp; Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" pagination="1 - 324" refId="ref8013" refString="Griswold, C. E., Ramirez, M. J., Coddington, J. A., Platnick, N. I. 2005. Atlas of phylogenetic data for entelegyne spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae: Entelegynae) with comments on their phylogeny. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 56 (Suppl. II): 1 - 324." type="journal article" year="2005">
Griswold 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEB9EEFC17168BFB85" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
) are absent in this family. However, after examining our own specimens, we found that feathery scales are actually present in both 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBD5DFBD317E2FBE3" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2015" box="[299,461,1068,1092]" class="Arachnida" genus="Longissipalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBD5DFBD317E2FBE3" box="[299,461,1068,1092]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Longissipalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBD89FBD3149AFBE3" authorityName="Wunderlich" authorityYear="2015" box="[511,693,1068,1092]" class="Arachnida" genus="Pedipalparaneus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBD89FBD3149AFBE3" box="[511,693,1068,1092]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Pedipalparaneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Thus, we do not distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBF9DFBD31322FBE3" authority="Jiang &amp; Li" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Li" box="[1003,1293,1068,1092]" class="Arachnida" family="Pilosarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pilosarachnidae Jiang &amp; Li</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEB961FBD31350FBE3" bold="true" box="[1303,1407,1068,1092]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">fam. nov.</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBCFEFBB0177FFBC0" box="[136,336,1103,1127]" class="Arachnida" family="Mongolarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mongolarachnidae</taxonomicName>
base on the existence of feathery scales.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="766F36CCFFD3FFFEBCCBFB8D1541FAB3" blockId="2.[136,1453,236,1544]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">
Additionally, 
<taxonomicName id="B1D04D4FFFD3FFFEBD22FB8D14AAFB2D" authority="Jiang &amp; Li" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Li" box="[340,645,1138,1162]" class="Arachnida" family="Pilosarachnidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pilosarachnidae Jiang &amp; Li</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="44A4EADEFFD3FFFEBEE2FB8E152DFB2D" bold="true" box="[660,770,1137,1162]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">fam. nov.</emphasis>
has a remarkable autapomorphy, the serrate structure on the prolateral-proximal margin of the tegulum, near the base of embolus (
<figureCitation id="EEEB2A49FFD3FFFEBF1DFB6B15CDFB0B" box="[875,994,1172,1196]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[155,218,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-71@5.[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pilosarachne ju Jiang &amp; Li, gen. &amp; sp. nov., holotype male. A. Left palp, retrolateral view. B. Bulb of left palp, ventral view. C. Right palp, dorsal view, horizontally flipped for the sake of comparison. D. Left palp, ventral view. Scale bars: A, Câ€“D=0.5 mm; B=0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5367239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5367239/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Figs 3B, D</figureCitation>
). This character is unique in comparison to other known spiders from 
<collectingRegion id="B414F82EFFD3FFFEBDD5FB4817DFFB68" box="[419,496,1207,1231]" country="Myanmar" name="Kachin" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Kachin</collectingRegion>
amber. However, the detailed structures on male palp are highly variable at species-level and shouldnâ€™t be considered for higher-level classification (
<bibRefCitation id="12414B3DFFD3FFFEBF57FB2515E7FB55" author="Ramirez" box="[801,968,1242,1266]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268" pagination="1 - 374" refId="ref8524" refString="Ramirez, M. J. 2014. The morphology and phylogeny of dionychan spiders (Araneae: Araneomorphae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 390: 1 - 374. doi: 10.1206 / 821.1." type="journal article" year="2014">RamÃ­rez, 2014</bibRefCitation>
), so we do not exclude the possibility that undiscovered species from the same family will lack such a structure.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="766F36CCFFD3FFFEBCCBFAE017BAFA43" blockId="2.[136,1453,236,1544]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">
Description. Medium-sized cribellate spider from 
<collectingRegion id="B414F82EFFD3FFFEBEBBFAE01535FA90" box="[717,794,1311,1335]" country="Myanmar" name="Kachin" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Kachin</collectingRegion>
amber. Three tarsal claws (
<figureCitation id="EEEB2A49FFD3FFFEB84EFAE01280FA90" box="[1080,1199,1311,1335]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[155,218,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-72@4.[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Pilosarachne ju Jiang &amp; Li, gen. &amp; sp. nov., holotype male. A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Tarsal claws of left leg II, lateral view. C. Tarsal claws of right leg II, ventral-apical view. D. Spinnerets, ventral view. E. Carapace, dorsal view. F. Chelicerae, anterior view. Scale bars: A=2.0mm; Bâ€“C, E=1.0mm; D, F =0.5mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5367237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5367237/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Figs 2Bâ€“C</figureCitation>
), serrate accessory claw setae present; eight eyes, ALE and PLE contiguous (
<figureCitation id="EEEB2A49FFD3FFFEBEC1FABE1525FAFD" box="[695,778,1345,1370]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[155,218,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-72@4.[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Pilosarachne ju Jiang &amp; Li, gen. &amp; sp. nov., holotype male. A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Tarsal claws of left leg II, lateral view. C. Tarsal claws of right leg II, ventral-apical view. D. Spinnerets, ventral view. E. Carapace, dorsal view. F. Chelicerae, anterior view. Scale bars: A=2.0mm; Bâ€“C, E=1.0mm; D, F =0.5mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5367237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5367237/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
); fovea distinct, longitudinal; body and appendages covered by dense feathery scales; spines numerous on legs but absent on tarsi, spines forming a ring at apex of each metatarsi (
<figureCitation id="EEEB2A49FFD3FFFEB93FFA9B13B0FADA" box="[1353,1439,1380,1405]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[155,218,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-72@4.[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Pilosarachne ju Jiang &amp; Li, gen. &amp; sp. nov., holotype male. A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Tarsal claws of left leg II, lateral view. C. Tarsal claws of right leg II, ventral-apical view. D. Spinnerets, ventral view. E. Carapace, dorsal view. F. Chelicerae, anterior view. Scale bars: A=2.0mm; Bâ€“C, E=1.0mm; D, F =0.5mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5367237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5367237/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
); paracymbium absent; tibia of male palp without apophyses, embolus with pars pendula (a membranous structure that accompanies embolus), conductor and median apophysis present, and with a serrate structure on tegulum, present near base of embolus (
<figureCitation id="EEEB2A49FFD3FFFEBD78FA3317A6FA43" box="[270,393,1484,1508]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[155,218,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-71@5.[216,1372,260,1960]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pilosarachne ju Jiang &amp; Li, gen. &amp; sp. nov., holotype male. A. Left palp, retrolateral view. B. Bulb of left palp, ventral view. C. Right palp, dorsal view, horizontally flipped for the sake of comparison. D. Left palp, ventral view. Scale bars: A, Câ€“D=0.5 mm; B=0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5367239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5367239/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">Figs 3Aâ€“D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="766F36CCFFD3FFFEBCCBFA101520F9AF" blockId="2.[136,1453,236,1544]" box="[189,783,1519,1544]" pageId="2" pageNumber="268">
Distribution. Late Cretaceous 
